@Robert Dean I think the problem here is your viewing femininity as weakness and masculinity  as strength. We aren’t cave men anymore, we have decided to follow certain societal rules in order to not live in a medieval blood bath. In doing this we have made a stand against monopolies of power and that can boil down to not attacking the vulnerable. Vulnerability is not just physical. A petite woman can be seen as vulnerable to a large man, but a manipulated or blackmailed man is also vulnerable.

@Robert Dean That is still a pretty ideological perspective. Maybe you have an unflinching ability to judge character, but if we are being realistic we can’t deny that manipulative people exist. These abused men aren’t masochists in search of violent brides. They find themselves married to someone who is abusive and in a position where self defence is not feasible. If a man defends himself against a violent women with one punch he can loose custody of his children, his career etc. It is that bad. My mother was extremely violent and it took my dad 7 years in court to gain full custody, because it is very unorthodox for the father to win in a custody battle with a mother. If he had hit her I’d have been living with her and she didn’t just abuse my dad. This is just not an issue that can be trivialised and turned into a joke about masculinity.

Agreed. Women asking for equality... are simply asking for equality. If they are only in it for themselves to obtain an advantage over another then that's not seeking equality in the first place. Should definitely be the same concept for men too. Its also worth asking the question: Why are these abused men unheard in the first place? Where lies the root of the problem and what is the root of the problem? I think its much more complicated than we are admitting and want to believe. Because the faulty social foundation was built and enforced for so long by one side. Unfortunately we arent working on level playing field because of that. I don't think we can really solve problems like these until we've solved the belittled view on women. This is just my theory but: That same oppression against females affects both men and women in completely unsymmetrical ways. The source or center point isnt even in the middle of the board. But women's rights directly impact men's rights because if they are equal then "feminine" traits won't be a breach of a man's supposed "superior" qualities just to make him ashamed and feel less than a man. Them being considered better only cripples them and indirectly dehumanizes them in a sense of being better than their counterparts even though they simply arent. So basically they are unknowingly fighting to be better than human when they simply cannot. Yet the problem is they assume they are the baseline human with woman being below that baseline. Of course not directing this to all men or anything moreso just stating the reality of our societal foundation, habits, and mentality. "Feminine" and "female" wouldn't be a direct insult. Therefore there would be no comparison and no need to keep up a "masculine" facade. A woman abusing a man would be seen just the same as a man abusing a woman. Because her "ability" to abuse and his "ability" to receive it wouldn't be underestimated. Can we get to that point? Probably not. People are to used to conflicts with patterns. We're used to massive problems like these displaced in entertainment and solved through illogical or "feel good" solutions. Instead of digging out the root we're constantly pruning leaves and hopelessly pointing out the fruits of our problem infinitely not realizing that the bush itself still stands regardless of how many leaves and fruits we pluck. A lot to read, I'd be surprised if anyone read it all.

About 6 months ago, I got out of an abusive relationship. She would scream, throw things, punch and claw me, lock herself in the bathroom and threaten suicide or cut herself if she didn't like something id said, threaten me with knives or really anything near her, and lots of other pretty textbook stuff. I started to get suicidal and extremely depressed, and when I tried to leave her the first time, she threw herself in front of a car. Already bruised and crying myself from her punching and throwing bottles and rocks at me, I had to demangle and resuscitate her. I remember the feeling of her heart and stuttered breathing stopping, and starting under my hands most nights, and the sound and sight of her spine hitting the signs. I remember being pried away by the EMTs once they showed up. She ultimately continued to use that night to keep me in her life, constantly threatening to do something like that again if I left her, all the while continuing to be violent and manipulative while I tried to take care of her in recovery. She blocked my friends and family, broke my phone, stole my money, cheated on me, nothing I could ever do was right. I still have scars on my hip, arms and head from bottles and stones, and in one case a steak knife. Its been half a year, and I still haven't stopped reliving those nights in my sleep, or been able to stop hearing the sound of her breaking, and the feel of her dying under my hands, and coming back. Or her screams when she woke. And even though I know its not my fault, I don't think I'll ever not feel guilty for trying to leave that night, and what she did when I tried. I'm in a much better place than I was after all that and thankfully I have some truly amazing friends that came to help me realize what I was putting myself through, one of whom im in a loving relationship with now. But its still hard. I don't think its something I'll ever truly get over. Part of why I struggled so hard to leave, aside from the fear and guilt, is that the first two people I tried to tell what was going on didn't believe me, one of them even beginning to cold shoulder me, and outright look down on me.  I'm no longer friends with them today, but back then I had thought they were very close to me. After that I didn't really try to reach out out of shame. It makes me feel a lot better seeing the rising support for people who've been through experiences similar. Thank you, all of you, for all the kind things you've said. And for being so vocal with your support. I hope you all know how far your words are carried
